## Problem

The sync command runs 4 sequential phases, each with its own independent Spinner:

1. \"Checking environment...\" → \"Environment OK\" (trivially fast, ~1ms)
2. \"Analyzing repository...\" → \"Analysis complete\" (calls Claude, 5-30s)
3. \"Fetching ADRs...\" → \"Fetched 20 ADRs\" (network, 1-5s)
4. \"Tailoring ADRs...\" → \"Tailored 20 ADRs into 1 files\" (calls Claude, 10-60s)

Each spinner runs independently and scrolls the terminal. After completion, you see a wall of checkmarks:

\`\`\`
  ✔ Environment OK
  ✔ Analysis complete
  ✔ Fetched 20 ADRs
  ✔ Tailored 20 ADRs into 1 files
\`\`\`

This is fine but doesn't communicate the overall pipeline progress. The user has no idea they're at step 2 of 4, or how long the whole process will take.

indicatif::MultiProgress (already available — indicatif 0.17 is in Cargo.toml:38) provides a managed group of progress bars that render together and can be updated independently.

## What the User Should See

### During execution (step 2 of 4):
\`\`\`
  ✔ Environment      checked
  ⠋ Analyzing        test-nextjs-project...
  · Fetching ADRs    waiting
  · Tailoring        waiting
\`\`\`

### After completion:
\`\`\`
  ✔ Environment      OK
  ✔ Analysis         1 project, 3 frameworks    2.1s
  ✔ Fetched          20 ADRs                    0.8s
  ✔ Tailored         20 ADRs → 1 file           4.3s
\`\`\`

Key improvements:
- All 4 phases visible at once (user sees full scope)
- Active phase has a spinner, upcoming phases show \"waiting\"
- Completed phases show timing
- Aligned columns for clean visual rhythm

## Implementation Plan

### Step 1: Create a SyncPipeline struct

\`\`\`rust
use indicatif::{MultiProgress, ProgressBar, ProgressStyle, ProgressDrawTarget};
use std::time::Instant;

pub struct SyncPipeline {
    multi: MultiProgress,
    bars: Vec<ProgressBar>,
    start_times: Vec<Option<Instant>>,
}

impl SyncPipeline {
    pub fn new(quiet: bool) -> Self {
        let multi = MultiProgress::new();
        if quiet {
            multi.set_draw_target(ProgressDrawTarget::hidden());
        }

        let phases = ["Environment", "Analysis", "Fetch ADRs", "Tailoring"];
        let waiting_style = ProgressStyle::with_template("  {prefix} {msg}").unwrap();
        let active_style = ProgressStyle::with_template("  {spinner} {prefix} {msg}").unwrap();

        let bars: Vec<ProgressBar> = phases.iter().map(|name| {
            let bar = multi.add(ProgressBar::new_spinner());
            bar.set_style(waiting_style.clone());
            bar.set_prefix(format!("· {:<14}", name));
            bar.set_message("waiting");
            bar
        }).collect();

        Self { multi, bars, start_times: vec![None; phases.len()] }
    }

    pub fn start_phase(&mut self, index: usize, message: &str) {
        self.start_times[index] = Some(Instant::now());
        self.bars[index].set_style(active_style());
        self.bars[index].set_message(message.to_string());
        self.bars[index].enable_steady_tick(Duration::from_millis(80));
    }

    pub fn finish_phase(&self, index: usize, message: &str) {
        let elapsed = self.start_times[index].map(|s| s.elapsed());
        let time_str = elapsed.map(|d| format!("{:.1}s", d.as_secs_f64())).unwrap_or_default();
        self.bars[index].set_style(done_style());
        self.bars[index].finish_with_message(format!("{:<30} {}", message, time_str));
    }
}
\`\`\`

### Step 2: Replace individual Spinners in run_sync()

Replace the 4 Spinner::new/success/error calls in sync.rs:83-222 with SyncPipeline calls:

\`\`\`rust
