## Problem

`InvocationOptions::for_tailoring` hardcodes `skip_permissions: true` (src/claude/options.rs:34-48), which causes `--allow-dangerously-skip-permissions` to be passed to every `claude --print` subprocess:

```rust
pub fn for_tailoring(model_override: Option<&str>) -> Self {
    Self {
        ...
        skip_permissions: true,  // always true, no matter what tools are configured
    }
}
```

This is a blanket suppression of ALL Claude Code permission checks. The intent is correct for the current read-only tool set (Read, Glob, Grep), but the implementation is fragile: if a future developer adds `Bash` or `Write` to the `tools` list without removing this flag, Claude will execute shell commands or write files without ever prompting the user for permission.

The flag name itself — "dangerously" — indicates this is a footgun.

## Fix

Two complementary changes:

1. **Add a compile-time / test-time assertion** that when `skip_permissions` is `true`, the tool list contains only known-safe read-only tools. Fail the test if `Bash`, `Write`, `Edit`, or `WebFetch` appear in the allowed tools list alongside `skip_permissions: true`.

```rust
#[test]
fn test_skip_permissions_only_with_readonly_tools() {
    let opts = InvocationOptions::for_tailoring(None);
    if opts.skip_permissions {
        let forbidden = ["Bash", "Write", "Edit", "WebFetch"];
        for tool in &forbidden {
            assert!(!opts.tools.contains(tool),
                "skip_permissions=true with unsafe tool: {tool}");
        }
    }
}
```

2. **(Optional, stronger):** Replace the flag with explicit per-tool `--allowedTools` grants. Claude Code honors `--allowedTools Read --allowedTools Glob --allowedTools Grep` without needing the skip flag. This removes the blanket suppression entirely.

